title: Add environment variables
body:
- add $LOG_FILE and $LOG_LEVEL

**EXAMPLE:**
\# You might use this kind of file as a `.env` file during project development. Because this file contains a GITHUB_TOKEN, you would not commit it to git (use a .gitignore file to effect this). You would use it by running ". .env" to set environment variables prior to interacting with your `run` CLI.

GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_nqp7EaHtK5SKzj5WEA2hRbsq6zeejjnnfuHwR
LOG_LEVEL=1
LOG_FILE=/Users/myUser/IdeaProjects/logs/mylog.txt

title: GitHub tokens
body: GitHub tokens should be provided specified by the environment variable $GITHUB_TOKEN

title: ./run test (test suite)
body:
- create 20+ test cases
- achieve 80%+ structural coverage
- output to stdout: “X/Y test cases passed. Z% line coverage achieved.”

**Example:**
Total: 10
Passed: 9
Coverage: 90%
9/10 test cases passed. 90% line coverage achieved.

title: parse all info (for metrics) from github and npm
body: - create 2 classes for github vs npm

title: concurrency for each metric
body:
- first, create threads for the functions for parsing the URL for each metric, then join the threads
- then, create threads for the functions for calculating scores for each metric, then join the threads

title: output log file
body:
- store in environment variable $LOG_FILE
- use verbosity level in environment variable $LOG_LEVEL

There are many views on what and how much to log. Some good resources are (1) [this blog](https://testing.googleblog.com/2013/06/optimal-logging.html); and (2) [this SO post](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2031163/when-to-use-the-different-log-levels).
